Coronavirus Pollution

October 04, 2020

We are using the Health dataset on air pollution across the world. Some of our initial questions are: How has pollution changed over time in relation to covid? Does it continue to vary based on changing policies? Are these trends country specific or region specific? Is there a pattern to where gets the most change in pollution?

Dataset:

Air Pollution: https://openaq.org/#/countries?_k=xqoof4

Goals:

Find if there is a correlation between coronavirus, coronavirus policies, and air pollution.

library(readr)
library(tidyverse)

Data and Methodology

LosAngeles <- read_csv("laAirset.csv")

Houston <- read_csv("openaq_HOU.csv")
Miami <- read_csv("openaq_MIA.csv")
Denver <- read_csv("openaq_DEN.csv")

The datasets aggregate PM2.5, PM10, ozone (O3), sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen dioxide (NO2), carbon monoxide (CO), and black carbon (BC) from “real-time government and research grade sources.” We chose to focus on ozone and nitrogen dioxide. Nitrogen dioxide’s main source is from the human combustion of fossil fuels, such as the fuel used in cars. Ozone is similarly formed when sunlight reacts to pollutants emitted by cars. Therefore, we decided to focus on these two because the most direct human impacts would be able to be seen. We then chose to study 11 major cities spread throughout the United States to get a larger variety of different location conditions. The cities chosen, in no particular order, were Los Angeles, Los Vegas, Chicago, Atlanta, Charlotte, New York, DC, Seattle, Houston, Miami, and Denver. Within each dataset, there were multiple data points at each location for multiple times throughout the day spanning January 2019 to present. These were averaged by month for each year at each location. Then the difference between 2019 and 2020 was plotted to account for the typical seasonal/monthly changes in pollutant levels. A horizontal line of zero was added to each.

Covid-19 on Air Pollution

Our research and analysis was to take the Health Sciences Data Set and correlate the number of cases that major cities around the United States had with the levels of Air Pollution that those major cities experienced. The first graph for each city shows the increase and decrease in the number of cases that city experienced, and the second graph is a graph we made using the data set that showed the air pollution level in that city in the same month. This pollution level was taken by finding the difference in means for the monthly averages of each pollutant from Jan 2019 to present. Overall, we saw that as the number of Covid-19 cases increased in major cities around the U.S., most cities saw a reduction in air pollution. This can be attributed to the fact that many major cities probably (and for the most part did) initiate drastic self-quarantining methods when outbreaks occurred. The lack of human activity outside likely allowed these air pollution levels to drop, meaning cleaner air for the citizens.

How to Interpret:

Each dip in the graph indicates a reduction in pollutants that is more than it usually would be at that time of year. The plot line at zero indicates no change in pollutant levels. While there could be natural changes in pollution levels unrelated to the pandemic, the assumption is that coronavirus was such a large scale event that any minute changes would not be enough to alter the massive trends. Generally, the nationwide response and panic surrounding the coronavirus started in March and these results can be seen as such in the graphs below.

Why it matters:

For the past few decades, scientists have been warning humans globally about the severe repercussions of climate change and what may happen to our planet if drastic measures are not taken. While the best solution would be to close all factories and ban all cars, this is not a realistic solution. Even though the Covid-19 virus has caused massive upheaval in everyone’s lives globally, it has forced humans to take these drastic measures that scientists were suggesting. When everyone in the U.S. was self-quarantining, the levels of air pollution severely declined and positively impacted the environment. Of course, this is not a sustainable method of helping the environment, but it did prove that given enough time and effort, humans could decrease the amount of pollution globally.

Cities

graph_pollutants <- function(data){
  US <- data %>%
    select(utc, value)
  US <- US %>%
    separate(utc, into=c("Date","Hour"),sep=" ",convert=T) %>%
    separate(Date, into=c("Year","Month","Day"),sep="-",convert=T)
  
  US <- US %>% 
    group_by(Year,Month) %>% 
    summarise(mean_value=mean(value)) %>%
    filter(Year>="2019" & Month<10) %>%
    ungroup()
  
  US <- US %>%
    group_by(Month) %>%
    summarise(diff_value=diff(mean_value))
  US %>%
    ggplot(mapping=aes(x=Month, y=diff_value)) + 
    geom_line() + 
    geom_point() + 
    scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(from=1,to=12, by = 1), labels=c("Jan","Feb","March","April","May","June","July","Aug","Sept","Oct","Nov","Dec")) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color="red")
}
